<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06259002 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06259002 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  WASHINGTON; STATE; RESTAURANT; ASSAULT; CLOSING; CONTROVERSY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  An assistant manager of a Taco Bell was fired for closing the restaurant afteryouths beat a customer and threatened to shoot him.;   The fast-food chainsaid Lee Sexton, 31, had no authority to close the restaurant.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  TACO BELL FIRES MANAGER FOR CLOSING AFTER ATTACKTEEN-AGERS BEAT BOY, THREATENED TO SHOOT  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     &quot;We have a responsibility to our customers,&quot; Taco Bell Vice President JackDaly said Thursday from corporate headquarters in Irvine. &quot;When a situationwarrants it, you may elect&quot; to close, he said. &quot;But this was not one of thoseisolated situations.&quot;;   Sexton said four or five teen-agers entered therestaurant late Sept. 5 and beat a boy they accused of being a skinhead, amember of the white-supremacist movement.;   Sexton ordered the youths toleave. On their way out, one turned and threatened to shoot the boy if hetried to leave.;   &quot;There were six other customers in the store at the timeand two of them were children,&quot; Sexton said. &quot;They all ducked. I locked thedoor and called police.&quot;;   When police arrived, they escorted the youth and afriend out. The victim didn't appear to need medical help, police Lt. WilliamMitchell said.;   Failing to reach two supervisors by telephone, Sexton said,she closed the restaurant and its drive-up window. The seating area normallycloses at 9 p.m.;   After talking to a supervisor, she reopened the drive-upwindow about one hour before its normal 11 p.m. closing time.;   &quot;Taco Bellmight have lost $30 worth of business,&quot; Sexton said. &quot;They were more concernedabout that than my customers being assaulted.&quot;;   Sexton said she would file acomplaint with the state Department of Labor.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  